{"format":"tiptap/v1","updatedAt":"2026-06-21T14:50:08.917Z","doc":{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sorting Algorithms"},{"type":"text","text":" rearrange data into a specific order (ascending, descending, or lexicographical) and are fundamental for enabling efficient searching, data preprocessing, and optimization in Gen AI. The most efficient general-purpose sorting algorithms (Merge Sort, Quick Sort, Heap Sort) achieve "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"O(n log n)"},{"type":"text","text":" time complexity, while simpler algorithms (Bubble, Insertion, Selection Sort) have "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"O(n²)"},{"type":"text","text":"—making them 100x slower for large datasets. In Gen AI, sorting is critical for sorting token probabilities, organizing training data, and implementing ranking/retrieval systems."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What It Is"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Aspect"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Definition"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Purpose"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Goal"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Rearrange elements in order (ascend